{"id":"1304.6754","submitter":"John R. Clem","authors":"John R Clem and A P Malozemoff","title":"Flux-transfer losses in helically wound superconducting power cables","comments":"20 pages, 4 figures, minor revisions recommended by referee","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0953-2048/26/8/085008","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Minimization of ac losses is essential for economic operation of\nhigh-temperature superconductor (HTS) ac power cables. A favorable\nconfiguration for the phase conductor of such cables has two counter-wound\nlayers of HTS tape-shaped wires lying next to each other and helically wound\naround a flexible cylindrical former. However, if magnetic materials such as\nmagnetic substrates of the tapes lie between the two layers, or if the winding\npitch angles are not opposite and essentially equal in magnitude to each other,\ncurrent distributes unequally between the two layers. Then, if at some point in\nthe ac cycle the current of either of the two layers exceeds its critical\ncurrent, a large ac loss arises from the transfer of flux between the two\nlayers. A detailed review of the formalism, its application to the case of\nparamagnetic substrates including the calculation of this flux transfer loss is\npresented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 24 Apr 2013 21:25:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 May 2013 01:43:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-15"}
